5000|$|On 1 October 1997, <b>Plaintiffs</b> Jessie Tompkins, Audra Beasley, James W. Scott, and Rodney Smith {{filed the}} Tompkins lawsuit {{on behalf of}} all non-white {{individuals}} similarly situated to <b>Plaintiffs.</b> In the <b>Plaintiff's</b> second amended complaint, the <b>plaintiffs</b> outlined class action grounds to eliminate the scholarship's race requirement. The <b>Plaintiffs</b> presented themselves as non-represented black citizens of the State of Alabama, and thus are members of the class certified in the Knight litigation (see below). <b>Plaintiffs</b> claim that the [...] "other-race" [...] scholarships created at Alabama State pursuant to the Court's 1995 Decree in Knight II violate their rights under the Fourteenth Amendment and 42 U.S.C.A. §§ 1981, 1983, and 2000d. The <b>Plaintiffs</b> named as Defendants the State of Alabama, ASU, the ASU Board of Trustees, and various ASU administrators. The <b>Plaintiffs</b> sought to certify this case as a class action pursuant to Federal Rules of Civil Procedure, Parts 23(b)(2) and 23(b)(3).|$|R
